# Core Conventions -- LinkedIn Autopilot V2

## Project Context
- Multi-agent LinkedIn content + engagement pipeline
- 40+ agents across 5 teams (Content, Engagement, Influencer, Profile, Learning)
- Python 3.11+, Docker, Anthropic Claude API
- Read CLAUDE.md (52 rules) and AGENTS.md before any work

## Commits
- Descriptive messages explaining WHY, not just WHAT
- One logical change per commit
- Never commit secrets, .env files, config/, data/, or credentials
- Update CHANGELOG.md for user-facing behavior changes

## Error Handling
- Every external call (API, DB, file) gets try/except with specific exception types
- Errors include context: what was attempted, what failed, and what to do about it
- Never swallow errors silently -- no bare `except:`
- Classify errors as FATAL vs RETRYABLE (CLAUDE.md Rule 30)
- Use circuit breaker pattern for LinkedIn API calls

## Code Style
- Follow existing patterns in the codebase
- All agents inherit from `BaseAgent` in `agents/base.py`
- Prompts live in `prompts/` as markdown files, never hardcoded
- Config from `config/business.yaml` via template variables `{{variable}}`
- Use `logging.getLogger(__name__)`, never `print()`

## Testing
- Manual testing: `python main.py --run <team>` (content|engagement|influencer|profile|all)
- Use `--dry-run` before touching scheduler intervals
- No "test post" language on public platforms (CLAUDE.md Rule 34)
- Run existing tests before committing

## Security
- No hardcoded secrets -- use environment variables via `os.getenv()`
- Validate all external inputs
- .gitignore includes .env, config/, data/, credentials
- LinkedIn cookies are sensitive -- never log or commit cookie values
- Browser sessions must be closed in `finally` blocks

## LinkedIn-Specific
- Respect rate limits -- engagement scheduler has built-in cooldowns
- All content passes Quality Editor + Fact Checker -- never bypass
- Embedding-based dedup prevents duplicate posts
- No hardcoded timezones -- read from config dynamically
